snippet.textDisplay:
this coronavirus being a 'plague' or even SARS is a lot of hyperbole if it doesn't drastically mutate beyond RNA norms -- otherwise you need to be coughed on (liquid droplets) within 1-2 meters and mostly just causes pneumonia ... which sucks but is rarely fatal unless you have preexisting conditions or are a senior. mutation risk is very low (tho possible). even SARS which killed nearly 1 in 10 basically never mutated (16 sequences and below RNA norms). and the main risk is this new coronavirus is pneumonia -- very rarely a mortal risk to healthy people.

that's not to say that tens of thousands of people getting pneumonia is not a major global health concern -- pneumonia is incredibly deadly to seniors or those with pre-existing conditions. But pneumonia isn't going to kill as many people as SARS. And after its mutation to infect humans, neither coronavirus likely would change much ... for this coronavirus to be as deadly as SARS even, it would need to mutate at an unusually high rate for an RNA -- and to be more deadly than SARS, mutate an almost unheard of rate.

risk of course is containment. If it stays years, then it may mutate enough to be much more deadly. That's why virus do deadly in the past. But we understand containment a lot better now.

snippet.textDisplay: The fact that in 2020 we're still powerless against viral diseases is to a large extent our fault as voters in democratic countries: we all elect politicians who won't put public funds into drug development and who, instead, rely purely on pharmaceutical companies for that. Pharmaceutical companies care about one thing, and one thing only: money. With regards to viruses - if a company doesn't think that they'll gain financially from developing therapies based on the numerous leads provided by academic research (that IS funded by the government and by charities), they won't pursue this avenue. Therefore, we, as voters, should demand that our elected representatives establish non-profit organizations working on developing therapies, with these organizations being funded by the public and working only to promote the public's health.
